image:image.image:title: Our Blog - Fishing Shirts Fully Customized
image:image.image:caption: Here are the steps for your customizing your new fishing shirts: Step 1: You send us a custom design, or we help create a design that you would like to have on your apparel. Step 2: Your custom design will be printed onto a sheet of high-release paper using our special sublimation dye. Step 3: The clothing fabric is laid onto a printed sheet and your artwork is then absorbed into the fabric using a heat press. (This is where the ink and material turn from a solid to a gas). Step 4: Once the heat is removed, the pores of the material are opened, and the ink can successfully permeate into the fibers to lock permanently into place. Step 5: Your custom fabric is then cut and sewn together to create your brand new custom sublimated apparel.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Step 1:
image:image.image:caption: The design is created To start, the printer takes the design they want to create on the finished product, and prints it out onto a transparent acetate film. This will be used to create the stencil.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Step 5:
image:image.image:caption: The ink is pressed through the screen onto the item The screen is lowered down onto the printing board. Ink is added to the top end of the screen, and a squeegee is used to pull the ink along the full length of the screen. This presses the ink through the open areas of the stencil, imprinting the design on the product underneath.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Step 3:
image:image.image:caption: The emulsion is washed off, creating the stencil After the screen has been exposed for a set time, the areas of the screen not covered by the design will have turned hard. Any unhardened emulsion is then carefully rinsed away. This leaves a clear imprint of the design on the screen for the ink to pass through.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Screen Printing
image:image.image:caption: Here at dasFlow, we also use Screen Printing. It is a technique of creating a picture or a design pattern by forcing ink or metal onto a surface through a screen of mesh. Using a stencil, or a series of stencils, the ink is distributed to the desired area(s) by being pressed through a porous screen, hence the name Screen Printing.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Step 2:
image:image.image:caption: The screen is prepared Next, the printer will choose a mesh screen to suit the complexity of the design, and the texture of the fabric being printed. The mesh screen is then coated with a layer of light-reactive emulsion, which will harden when developed under bright light.

image:image.image:title: Screen Printing - Step 4:
image:image.image:caption: The Item Is Prepared For Print The screen is then placed on the printing press. The item or garment being printed is laid down flat onto the printing board, underneath the screen.
